{
  "doc_id": "12160",
  "text": "In the context of the present study, the role of NO is of particular interest given its responsiveness to variations in blood flow. Specifically, as blood flow increases, there is an increase in the shear stress acting on the vessel. With the increases in arterial blood flow that accompanies exercise, shear stress stimulates activity of the NO-dilator system, including the up-regulation of endothelial-derived NO synthase, to buffer the increased shear [CITATION_1] . Although the precise mechanisms have yet to be elucidated, the increased activity of the NO-dilator system is associated with the modulation of platelet, macrophage and endothelial derived growth factors that favors increased LD and reductions in arterial TWT. This arterial remodeling continues until the shear stress is normalized and the NO activity returns back to baseline levels [CITATION_2] .",
